<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What are HTTP headers?", answer: "HTTP headers are key-value pairs sent between a client (browser) and server with every HTTP request and response. They carry metadata about the message, such as the content type, encoding, caching rules, authentication credentials, and security policies. Headers are invisible to users but essential for how browsers and servers communicate. Each header follows the format 'Header-Name: value' and appears on its own line." },
  { question: "What are security headers and why do they matter?", answer: "Security headers are HTTP response headers that instruct browsers to enable or disable specific security features. They prevent attacks like cross-site scripting (XSS), clickjacking, MIME sniffing, and protocol downgrade attacks. Key security headers include Content-Security-Policy (prevents XSS), Strict-Transport-Security (forces HTTPS), X-Frame-Options (prevents clickjacking), and X-Content-Type-Options (prevents MIME sniffing). Missing security headers leave websites vulnerable to common attacks." },
  { question: "What does Content-Security-Policy do?", answer: "Content-Security-Policy (CSP) is the most powerful security header. It tells the browser which sources of content are trusted for scripts, styles, images, fonts, frames, and other resources. By restricting where code can execute from, CSP is the primary defense against cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks. A strict CSP can prevent inline scripts, eval(), and loading resources from untrusted domains." },
  { question: "What is Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS)?", answer: "Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS) tells browsers to only connect to the site using HTTPS, even if the user types http:// or follows an HTTP link. The max-age directive specifies how long the browser should remember this rule (typically one year or 31536000 seconds). The includeSubDomains directive extends the policy to all subdomains. HSTS prevents SSL stripping attacks where an attacker downgrades an HTTPS connection to HTTP." },
  { question: "How do I get my site's HTTP headers?", answer: "You can view HTTP headers using browser developer tools (Network tab), the curl command (curl -I https://example.com), or online tools. In Chrome or Firefox, press F12, go to the Network tab, reload the page, and click on the main request to see both request and response headers. Copy the response headers and paste them into this tool for analysis." }
]) %>

